For example, the highlight of the middle section is when Fu Qingfeng slowly rises into mid-air after being poisoned by a monster, Ning Caichen kisses her while spinning against the background of a green light, creating a strange atmosphere that is both sacred and magical. The evil monk Puducihang makes a solemn but bizarre appearance in the guise of Buddha, and the three-dimensional images by computer stunts are unforgettable to the audience. After the battle with the centipede monster, firstly, Zuo Qianhu is attacked by a monster who appears out of nowhere. Then, Yan Chixia uses a series of swordsmanship. Suddenly, the centipede monster pops up from the ground and everyone flies on their swords. And finally, Yan Chixia and Zhi Qius spirits leave their bodies and merge into their swords. The film style is very realistic, which can make the audience feel as if they were there, although the plot is not new. The biggest highlight is that the Shaolin Kung Fu is knocked off its pedestal, because it is no longer invincible in the film and Shaolin Temple is not indestructible either. When the audience do not focus on the Kung Fu, they become aware that the Shaolin Spirit is the most valuable and the most powerful. After Hou Jie enters Shaolin Temple for the first time, he arrogantly writes Nothing special on the plaque. However, when he really catches on the spirit, he feels ashamed and tries to wipe what he wrote with water at night. Unarmed, the young monks walk towards the soldiers under a rain of bullets, which shows the power of humanity and righteousness. In the film, although the Abbot of Shaolin Temple looks like an ordinary man, he holds back all the enemy forces when he helps others retreat. Although the subject itself is not the traditional mystery, the director Sheng Ding uses high-speed lens to create a strong sense of tension and realism. This kind of narrative method of knowing the result from the beginning, and then inferring the rescue based on the clues in the incident, is impressive. goal_topic: A Chinese Ghost Story II:The Tao In Human World
knowledge: Love You More Each Day, Comments, With the release of A Chinese Ghost Story II, Tsui Harks film reached a technical peak. The films visual images are magical and fantastical, successfully blending the new and the classical, the realistic and the supernatural. In the film, Tsui Hark has spared no effort in experimenting with various cinematographic techniques, resulting in a series of computer-aided special effects, in addition to tall ghosts and giant centipede monsters made from physical models. For example, the highlight of the middle section is when Fu Qingfeng slowly rises into mid-air after being poisoned by a monster, Ning Caichen kisses her while spinning against the background of a green light, creating a strange atmosphere that is both sacred and magical. The evil monk Puducihang makes a solemn but bizarre appearance in the guise of Buddha, and the three-dimensional images by computer stunts are unforgettable to the audience. After the battle with the centipede monster, firstly, Zuo Qianhu is attacked by a monster who appears out of nowhere. Then, Yan Chixia uses a series of swordsmanship. Suddenly, the centipede monster pops up from the ground and everyone flies on their swords. And finally, Yan Chixia and Zhi Qius spirits leave their bodies and merge into their swords. The flying sword blows up the centipede monster. But Zhi Qius spirit cannot go back to his body and disappears in the sky. Its an imaginative and smooth performance.

When the audience do not focus on the Kung Fu, they become aware that the Shaolin Spirit is the most valuable and the most powerful. After Hou Jie enters Shaolin Temple for the first time, he arrogantly writes Nothing special on the plaque. However, when he really catches on the spirit, he feels ashamed and tries to wipe what he wrote with water at night. Unarmed, the young monks walk towards the soldiers under a rain of bullets, which shows the power of humanity and righteousness. knowledge: Love You More Each Day, Comments, With the release of A Chinese Ghost Story II, Tsui Harks film reached a technical peak. The films visual images are magical and fantastical, successfully blending the new and the classical, the realistic and the supernatural. In the film, Tsui Hark has spared no effort in experimenting with various cinematographic techniques, resulting in a series of computer-aided special effects, in addition to tall ghosts and giant centipede monsters made from physical models. For example, the highlight of the middle section is when Fu Qingfeng slowly rises into mid-air after being poisoned by a monster, Ning Caichen kisses her while spinning against the background of a green light, creating a strange atmosphere that is both sacred and magical. The evil monk Puducihang makes a solemn but bizarre appearance in the guise of Buddha, and the three-dimensional images by computer stunts are unforgettable to the audience. After the battle with the centipede monster, firstly, Zuo Qianhu is attacked by a monster who appears out of nowhere. Then, Yan Chixia uses a series of swordsmanship. Suddenly, the centipede monster pops up from the ground and everyone flies on their swords. And finally, Yan Chixia and Zhi Qius spirits leave their bodies and merge into their swords. The flying sword blows up the centipede monster. But Zhi Qius spirit cannot go back to his body and disappears in the sky. Its an imaginative and smooth performance.
